<paragraph id="193A36E4FF930444ECF9FA6BFE8589A4" blockId="10.[151,1436,152,1840]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF930444ECF9FA6BFE908AEA" bold="true" box="[198,364,1427,1453]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Observations</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF930444EDADFA6CFD5B8AEA" authorityName="Leme &amp; L. Kollmann" authorityYear="2011" box="[402,679,1428,1453]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Aechmea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="recurvipetala">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF930444EDADFA6CFD5B8AEA" box="[402,679,1428,1453]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Aechmea recurvipetala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found during a 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF930444EF8BFA6CFBA98AE9" box="[948,1109,1428,1454]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Bromeliaceae</taxonomicName>
survey conducted in Alto Cariri State Park with the support of the Instituto Estadual de Florestas (IEF) of 
<collectingRegion id="DB41F806FF930444E879FA42FB1B8A93" box="[1094,1255,1466,1492]" country="Brazil" name="Minas Gerais" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Minas Gerais</collectingRegion>
. It is a member of 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF930444EC88FA19FEDE8ABD" box="[183,290,1505,1530]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Aechmea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF930444EC88FA19FEDE8ABD" box="[183,290,1505,1530]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Aechmea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF930444ED9FFA19FCA08ABC" authority="(Gaudich. ex Beer) Baker" authorityName="Baker" baseAuthorityName="Beer" box="[416,860,1505,1531]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Chevaliera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF930444ED9FFA19FDDE8ABD" box="[416,546,1505,1530]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Chevaliera</emphasis>
(Gaudich. ex Beer) Baker
</taxonomicName>
, and belongs to the 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF930444E877FA19FB368ABD" box="[1096,1226,1505,1530]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Aechmea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="conifera">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF930444E877FA19FB368ABD" box="[1096,1226,1505,1530]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">A. conifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species complex. The closest relative is 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF930444EDA4F9F0FCD08965" authority="Leme (2010: 131)" authorityName="Leme" authorityPageNumber="131" authorityYear="2010" box="[411,812,1544,1570]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Aechmea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="heterosepala">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF930444EDA4F9F0FDAD8966" box="[411,593,1544,1569]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">A. heterosepala</emphasis>
Leme (2010: 131)
</taxonomicName>
, from which the new species differs by its erect floral bracts (vs. suberect), which are distinctly imbricate (vs. not imbricate toward the apex), not forming any pouches around the flowers (vs. forming a distinct utricle around the flowers); shorter sepals (
<quantity id="DE7D9B01FF930444E8CEF9ADFA8E8928" box="[1265,1394,1621,1647]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="22.5" valueMax="23.0" valueMin="22.0">22–23 mm</quantity>
vs. 
<quantity id="DE7D9B01FF930444ECA8F984FEEA89D1" box="[151,278,1660,1686]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.95" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.9" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="29.5" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="29.0">29–30 mm</quantity>
long) with a mucronate apex (vs. apex long subulate-cuspidate), and by the narrowly ovate petals (vs. narrowly spatulate), which are shorter (
<quantity id="DE7D9B01FF930444EE88F95AFCC089FB" box="[695,828,1698,1724]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="22.0" valueMax="23.0" valueMin="21.0">21–23 mm</quantity>
vs. 
<quantity id="DE7D9B01FF930444EF4DF95AFC0489FB" box="[882,1016,1698,1724]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.35" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="3.2" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="33.5" valueMax="35.0" valueMin="32.0">32–35 mm</quantity>
) and strongly spirally recurved at anthesis (vs. erect).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="193A36E4FF930444ECF9F908FBF98877" blockId="10.[151,1436,152,1840]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Since the identification of the species of the 
<taxonomicName id="DE854D67FF930444EEE3F908FCA3884E" box="[732,863,1776,1801]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Aechmea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="conifera">
<emphasis id="2BF1EAF6FF930444EEE3F908FCA3884E" box="[732,863,1776,1801]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">A. conifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex can be a difficult task due to a similar general appearance of the species, an idenfitication key is presented below.
</paragraph>
